Thank you, that is wonderful to have! The code looks good to me, but I didn't validate all the details, hope someone with more HBase-trx expertise can have a look. I also hope that this solution will port well to HBase 1.0.

I am wondering whether we still need to build four different jar files for HBase-trx, given that we use Java reflection to figure out which interfaces to use. That's a general question, not directly related to this change.

I would prefer that we not merge this code so long as it removes transactional capabilities for native HBase tables. That feature is something that is advertised as a Trafodion feature, so we should not regress it. If we can fix this issue, then I'd be glad to merge this.

Now, MT-DCS use random.nextInt(1000) to generator a number for statement which used as stmtHandle. However it can't make sure the value it unique for echo statement. hashCode() could be used instead of random.
I have test it.In the test When using random.nextInt() it will generator a reduplicate stmtHandle after I creating 20 statements.
The change looks fine. I'm wondering, though, if hashcode() could return duplicate values? (Perhaps it does so much less frequently.)
jenkins, retest -- jenkins script was not properly updated to source env.sh for docs build
jenkins, retest -- trafodion env requires bash shell
JVM can guarantee it's unique. However I think it may return duplicate if there are more than 2^32 objects since it's a INT value. But I don't think we need consider this situation。
Tests revealed an issue.  Some compile-time dependencies are causing failure for site phase of building the docs.  Will need some re-work.  More to come.
Looks good to me. New code is simpler which is nice.

While I agree that a duplicate is less likely with this change, I'm wondering what the impact is when there is a duplicate. Is this still a serious problem from a user perspective? If the objective is simply to get a unique statement identifier, would it make sense to detect that a duplicate occurred and then add a retry loop that would just increment the value until a unique statement identifier is achieved?
